We have shown that, given our entropy conditions, the entropy passing
through a lightsheet is bounded by one quarter the difference in area of
the two bounding spatial surfaces.  This is precisely the statement of the
generalized Bousso bound.

It is interesting to note that nowhere in the proof did we need to use the
contracting lightsheet condition.  The only indication that we should
choose a contracting lightsheet comes from the boundary condition
ii .  We see from condition ii  that, in order to allow a
positive, future-directed entropy flux, the derivative of 
must be negative.  If the lightsheet were expanding at , then
a timelike entropy flux would have to be past-directed at .

Note also that Bousso's entropy bound can be saturated only if 
for all .  In light of the Raychaudhuri equation (),
we see that  and the shear  must be zero everywhere
along the lightsheet in order for  to remain zero.  The bound can be
saturated only in this most trivial scenario.  This will not be the case
for other gravitational theories we will study, such as the CGHS dilaton
model, where saturation of the bound can occur in the presence of matter.


Spherical reduction 

Our goal is to study the entropy bound in two dimensional models where
our semiclassical analysis will be greatly simplified.
As a guide to what phenomenological conditions we should be using
in 2D models, we will first rederive the previous proof for the
purely spherical sector of 4D Einstein-Hilbert gravity.

We begin with the 4D Einstein-Hilbert action coupled to some matter
Lagrangian density, :
 
